description:
## Severity: HIGH

## Summary
SCIM token validation uses standard string equality (==) instead of a constant-time comparison, making it vulnerable to timing attacks.

## Finding
**File:** src/Modules/Identity/Foundry.Identity.Infrastructure/Services/ScimService.cs:157-167

```csharp
public async Task<bool> ValidateTokenAsync(string token, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    // ...
    string hashedToken = HashToken(token);
    return config.BearerToken == hashedToken;  // <-- Standard string comparison
}
```

Note: The API key validation (RedisApiKeyService) avoids this by using hash-based lookup (hash the key, look up by hash in Redis), which is inherently timing-safe. But SCIM token comparison is a direct string comparison.

## Impact
An attacker could use timing side-channels to recover the token hash byte-by-byte, potentially allowing SCIM API access.

## Required Fix
Use `CryptographicOperations.FixedTimeEquals()` for the comparison. Convert both hash strings to byte arrays (UTF-8) and compare with the constant-time method:
```csharp
byte[] expectedBytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(config.BearerToken);
byte[] actualBytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(hashedToken);
return CryptographicOperations.FixedTimeEquals(expectedBytes, actualBytes);
```
